  "local_port": 56136,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are examples of prefixes and suffixes?",
  "response": "Prefixes and suffixes are types of **affixes**, which are groups of letters added to the beginning or end of a root word to modify its meaning or create a new word. Understanding prefixes and suffixes can help you expand your vocabulary and improve your comprehension of complex words.\n\n### **Prefixes**\nPrefixes are added to the **beginning** of a root word. They often change the meaning of the word in a specific way. Here are some common prefixes with examples:\n\n1. **Un-** (meaning \"not\" or \"the opposite of\")\n   - **Unhappy** (not happy)\n   - **Undo** (reverse the doing)\n\n2. **Re-** (meaning \"again\" or \"back\")\n   - **Rewrite** (write again)\n   - **Return** (come back)\n\n3. **Dis-** (meaning \"not\" or \"opposite of\")\n   - **Dislike** (not like)\n   - **Disconnect** (separate connection)\n\n4. **Pre-** (meaning \"before\")\n   - **Preview** (view before)\n   - **Preheat** (heat before)\n\n5. **Mis-** (meaning \"wrongly\" or \"incorrectly\")\n   - **Misunderstand** (understand wrongly)\n   - **Misplace** (place incorrectly)\n\n6. **Sub-** (meaning \"under\" or \"below\")\n   - **Submarine** (underwater vessel)\n   - **Substandard** (below standard)\n\n7. **Inter-** (meaning \"between\" or \"among\")\n   - **International** (between nations)\n   - **Interact** (act between)\n\n8. **Over-** (meaning \"too much\" or \"excessive\")\n   - **Overwork** (work too much)\n   - **Overcharge** (charge excessively)\n\n### **Suffixes**\nSuffixes are added to the **end** of a root word. They can change the word\u2019s form, such as turning a noun into an adjective, or modify its meaning. Here are some common suffixes with examples:\n\n1. **-ness** (turns adjectives into nouns, meaning \"state of\")\n   - **Happiness** (state of being happy)\n   - **Darkness** (state of being dark)\n\n2. **-ful** (meaning \"full of\")\n   - **Joyful** (full of joy)\n   - **Careful** (full of care)\n\n3. **-less** (meaning \"without\")\n   - **Fearless** (without fear)\n   - **Hopeless** (without hope)\n\n4. **-ly** (turns adjectives into adverbs)\n   - **Quickly** (in a quick manner)\n   - **Brightly** (in a bright manner)\n\n5. **-able / -ible** (meaning \"capable of\" or \"worthy of\")\n   - **Readable** (capable of being read)\n   - **Flexible** (capable of bending)\n\n6. **-ment** (turns verbs into nouns, indicating an action or process)\n   - **Enlightenment** (the process of becoming enlightened)\n   - **Development** (the process of developing)\n\n7. **-tion / -sion** (turn verbs into nouns, indicating action or condition)\n   - **Creation** (the act of creating)\n   - **Expansion** (the act of expanding)\n\n8. **-er / -or** (indicates a person or thing that performs an action)\n   - **Teacher** (a person who teaches)\n   - **Actor** (a person who acts)\n\n9. **-ous** (turns nouns into adjectives, meaning \"full of\")\n   - **Famous** (full of fame)\n   - **Dangerous** (full of danger)\n\n10. **-ify / -ize** (turns nouns or adjectives into verbs, indicating making or becoming)\n    - **Simplify** (make simple)\n    - **Realize** (become aware of)\n\n### **Examples in Context**\n\n- **Prefix Example:**\n  - **Impossible**: The prefix **im-** (meaning \"not\") is added to **possible** to mean \"not possible.\"\n\n- **Suffix Example:**\n  - **Caregiver**: The suffix **-er** is added to **caregive** (from \"caregive\" as a verb) to indicate \"a person who cares.\"\n\n### **Tips for Using Prefixes and Suffixes**\n\n1. **Understand the Root Word:** Knowing the base meaning helps you see how the prefix or suffix alters it.\n2. **Learn Common Affixes:** Familiarize yourself with the most common prefixes and suffixes to recognize patterns.\n3. **Practice with Examples:** Apply prefixes and suffixes to different root words to see how meanings change.\n4. **Use Context Clues:** In sentences, use the surrounding words to help infer the meaning of unfamiliar words with affixes.\n\nBy mastering prefixes and suffixes, you can greatly enhance your ability to decipher and construct a wide array of words, making your communication more effective and nuanced.",
